COPY public.copywriter_rules (id, content, updated_at, brand_id) FROM stdin;
1	THE VOICE IN ONE LINE\nShort. Confident. Specific. Never explains itself.\n\nWHAT THIS VOICE DOES\n- One idea per caption. That is enough.\n- Ends on a statement, not a question.\n- Specific over general. Always.\n- Confident without describing. Show, don't enthuse.\n- Never tells the audience what to feel.\n- Rhythm matters. Read it aloud. If it doesn't land, it isn't done.\n- Maximum 3 short paragraphs. Usually fewer.\n\nWHAT TO NEVER DO\n- Never write more than 3 short paragraphs.\n- Never open with a scene-setting sentence. ("May is one of those months...", "There's something about this time of year..." are banned.)\n- Never explain why Sicily or Malta is good. State the fact, let the destination carry it.\n- Never use atmospheric filler. Banned: "the light is something else entirely", "the heat is building", "the crowds haven't arrived yet", "the air is different", "something about this season", "there's nowhere quite like".\n- Never sound like a tourism board. If it could appear in a travel brochure, rewrite it.\n- Never use hashtags. Not one.\n- Never use an em dash with spaces (" — " or "— "). Use a comma, line break, or full stop instead.\n- Never write "the schedule is live", "just dropped", or "now available" — the timetable is always there.\n\nHARD RULES\n- No hashtags ever.\n- One exclamation mark maximum per caption, only when earned.\n- CTAs only when they add something. Woven into the caption — never as a standalone line.\n- Sentence length: vary it. Short punches matter. So does rhythm.\n- Do not use occasions such as Mother’s Day, Father’s Day, or Christmas for promotional purposes; they should be acknowledged only with well wishes.\n\nWEEKLY SCHEDULE — SPECIFIC STANDARD\nThe weekly schedule runs every Saturday. Caption frame: here's what's crossing this week, pick your day.\nTone: informative but human. Flexibility and frequency are the message.\nOpen with a calendar emoji. End with the timetable link.\nNever frame it as an announcement or a launch.\n\nOFFER COPY\nLead with the human benefit, not the price.\n"€63.60" is not a headline. Build to the number.\nAlways direct to virtuferries.com for booking.\n\nNEVER USE THESE WORDS\nparadise, breathtaking, unforgettable, hidden gem, postcard-perfect, magical, stunning, incredible, vibrant, bustling	2026-04-16 20:31:18.476	1
2	THE VOICE IN ONE LINE\nCalm, plain, helpful. Sound like the crew, not the marketing team.\n\nWHAT THIS VOICE DOES\n- One idea per caption. No second thought tacked on.\n- Leads with the practical thing: the date, the route, the time, the change.\n- Plain English. Factual over poetic. Helpful over clever.\n- Confident without flourish. State it once and move on.\n- Treats the audience as adults who already know Gozo is worth visiting.\n- Rhythm matters. If it sounds like a leaflet, rewrite it.\n- 1-2 short sentences for service posts. 2-3 for spotlights. Never more.\n\nPOST STRUCTURE — applies to every post type unless overridden\n- Every post starts with a SHORT BOLD HEADLINE on its own line.\n- Headlines use Unicode Sans-Serif Bold (e.g. "𝗦𝗮𝗶𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘀 𝗖𝗮𝗻𝗰𝗲𝗹𝗹𝗲𝗱"), NOT all caps, NOT markdown asterisks.\n- After the headline: blank line, then 1-2 short sentence body, then blank line, then CTA line.\n- CTA line uses an emoji (👉 for action, 🌐 for a link) and the brand domain in CamelCase: GozoHighspeed.com.\n- Service Update REMOVALS are the exception: no URL, no booking link. Service Update ADDITIONS get a CTA.\n- Fleet Highlights are a FULL exception to this structure: NO bold headline, NO multi-block layout, NO CTA, NO URL, NO mention of GozoHighspeed.com. Just one short sentence-case line, often trailing off with "…" or ending with a single emoji like 🌊. The image carries the post.\n\nWHAT TO NEVER DO\n- Never open with hype: "exciting news", "we're thrilled", "big announcement", "did you know".\n- Never use ALL CAPS for emphasis on any word. Use Unicode Sans-Serif Bold instead.\n- Never use emojis in the body opening sentence (only in the headline flag and CTA line).\n- Never use exclamation marks on a Service Update or timetable. Tone is calm, not loud.\n- Never use tourist-brochure language. Banned: "hidden gem", "must-see", "paradise", "breathtaking", "magical", "stunning", "unforgettable", "vibrant".\n- Never invent FALSE urgency. Real availability cues like "selling fast", "last call", "before it's too late" are fine on booking-type posts because they reflect real seat scarcity — but never on Service Update posts.\n- Never use hashtags.\n- Never use an em dash with spaces (" — " or "— "). Use a comma, line break, or full stop instead.\n- Never describe Gozo. Anchor it with a real, specific detail (a place, a sound, a time of day).\n\nHARD RULES\n- No hashtags ever.\n- The brand domain is always written GozoHighspeed.com (CamelCase). Never gozohighspeed.com, never www.gozohighspeed.com.\n- Date format: weekday + ordinal day + month, e.g. "Thursday 30th April". Multiple dates: "April 20th, 25th & 30th".\n- Time format: 24-hour, e.g. "07:45".\n- No exclamation marks on Service Updates, timetables, booking reminders, fares, or general announcements. Spotlights and fleet highlights may use one, only when earned.\n- CTAs are their own line at the end, prefixed with 👉 or 🌐. Service notices have no CTA line.\n- Sentence length: short. Vary cadence. Read it aloud before posting.\n- Do not use occasions such as Mother's Day, Father's Day, or Christmas for promotional purposes; acknowledge with well wishes only.\n\nSERVICE UPDATE STANDARD\nCovers any change to the schedule — REMOVALS (cancellations, suspensions) AND ADDITIONS (extra sailings, new trips). One post type, two polarities.\nHeadline is a flag, not a summary. Polarity determines the emoji:\n  - REMOVALS: "🔴 𝗜𝗺𝗽𝗼𝗿𝘁𝗮𝗻𝘁: 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝘃𝗶𝗰𝗲 𝗨𝗽𝗱𝗮𝘁𝗲"\n  - ADDITIONS: "🟢 𝗘𝘅𝘁𝗿𝗮 𝗦𝗮𝗶𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘀 𝗔𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱" or "🟢 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝘃𝗶𝗰𝗲 𝗨𝗽𝗱𝗮𝘁𝗲"\nThe specific change goes in the body, not the headline.\nBody opens with the reason ("Due to ..."), then names the change and the dates.\nClosing depends on the type:\n  - REMOVAL — Planned (events, scheduled work): practical planning tip, e.g. "you can book online up to 30 minutes before departure to guarantee your seat".\n  - REMOVAL — Unplanned (weather, mechanical, sea conditions): "Updates to follow."\n  - ADDITION: a booking CTA, e.g. "👉 Book your seat: GozoHighspeed.com".\nNEVER include a URL on a REMOVAL post. ADDITIONS get a CTA — extra capacity needs a booking nudge.\nTone: calm and informative. Never apologetic or dramatic on removals. Never hyped on additions.\n\nTIMETABLE STANDARD\nState the dates the schedule covers and the crossing frequency in plain terms. Direct to GozoHighspeed.com for the full schedule. Never frame it as "just dropped" or "now live" — it has always been there.\n\nBOOKING REMINDER STANDARD\nLead with the practical reason to book now (the season, the date, the peak window, the seat scarcity). One nudge, no false pressure.\n\nFARES & OFFERS STANDARD\nLead with the value the rider gets, then the price. Plain and transparent. Build to the number, never headline it.\n\nDESTINATION OR EVENT SPOTLIGHT STANDARD\nOpen with one real, specific sensory detail or moment in Gozo — not a generic adjective. Anchor it back to the 35-minute crossing.\n\nNEVER USE THESE WORDS\nparadise, breathtaking, unforgettable, hidden gem, postcard-perfect, magical, stunning, incredible, vibrant, bustling, exciting news, we're thrilled, big announcement	2026-04-29 21:25:09.303184	2
\.
