COPY public.voice_profiles (id, brand_id, post_type, tone, length, opening, cta, avoid, anchor_example, updated_at) FROM stdin;
4	2	Destination or Event Spotlight	Warm, evocative, grounded in real detail. Sound like someone who knows Gozo.	2–3 sentences. Paint a picture, then anchor it.	A specific sensory detail or moment — not 'Did you know…'.	Tie back to the crossing — 35 minutes from Malta.	Tourist-brochure language, 'hidden gem', 'must-see', clichéd adjectives.	Sunday mornings in Victoria's Citadel are quiet enough to hear the church bells echo across the valley. 35 minutes from Malta — book at gozohighspeed.com.	2026-04-29 20:38:10.457383
5	2	General Announcement	Clear, on-brand, neutral-positive. The default Gozo Highspeed voice.	2–3 short sentences.	Lead with the news itself, not framing or build-up.	Only if natural — otherwise close on the news.	'We are excited to announce', 'big news!', filler intros.	Our new mobile-friendly booking flow is live. Faster checkout, clearer timetables — try it at gozohighspeed.com.	2026-04-29 20:38:10.46056
6	2	Timetable	Purely informational, scannable, zero fluff.	1–2 sentences. If multiple times are involved, keep them in a clean list.	Open with the period the timetable covers (date range or season).	Point to the full timetable on gozohighspeed.com.	Adjectives, hype, emojis, exclamation marks.	Summer timetable, 1 June – 30 September: departures every 45 minutes from 06:00 to 22:30. Full schedule at gozohighspeed.com.	2026-04-29 20:38:10.465963
7	2	Fares & Offers	Plain, transparent, value-led. Promotional but never shouty.	1–2 sentences. State the offer, the dates, the action.	Lead with the price or the saving — concrete, not vague.	'Book at gozohighspeed.com' woven into the close.	'Unbeatable!!', 'crazy deal', exclamation marks, all caps, fake urgency.	Return crossings from €23 throughout May. Book your dates at gozohighspeed.com.	2026-04-29 20:38:10.469646
1	2	Service Update	Calm, plain, helpful. Same crew voice for both bad news (cancellations) and good news (added trips). Never apologetic, never overhyped.	Bold flag headline + 1-2 sentence body opening with the reason + closing line (planning tip, 'Updates to follow', or CTA — depends on polarity). Three short blocks separated by blank lines.	Sans-Serif Bold flag headline. POLARITY DETERMINES THE EMOJI:\n- REMOVALS (cancellation, suspension, schedule reduction): '🔴 𝗜𝗺𝗽𝗼𝗿𝘁𝗮𝗻𝘁: 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝘃𝗶𝗰𝗲 𝗨𝗽𝗱𝗮𝘁𝗲'\n- ADDITIONS (extra sailings, new trips, expanded service): '🟢 𝗘𝘅𝘁𝗿𝗮 𝗦𝗮𝗶𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘀 𝗔𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱' or '🟢 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝘃𝗶𝗰𝗲 𝗨𝗽𝗱𝗮𝘁𝗲'\nThe specific change goes in the body, never in the headline.	POLARITY DETERMINES THE CLOSE:\n- REMOVALS: NO CTA, NO URL, NO booking link. Close instead with either:\n  • Planned (events, scheduled work): practical planning tip, e.g. 'You can book online up to 30 minutes before departure to guarantee your seat.'\n  • Unplanned (weather, mechanical, sea conditions): 'Updates to follow.'\n- ADDITIONS: Close with a CTA inviting the booking, e.g. '👉 Book your seat: GozoHighspeed.com'.	Apologies ('we're sorry', 'apologies for the inconvenience'), drama ('unfortunately', 'we regret'), hype on additions ('exciting news', 'big announcement', 'we're thrilled'), exclamation marks, ALL CAPS, hashtags. Never include a URL on a removal/cancellation post. Don't promise specific resumption times unless confirmed. Don't add inventory urgency to additions ('selling fast', 'before it fills up') — let the booking link do the work.	REMOVAL EXAMPLE:\n🔴 𝗜𝗺𝗽𝗼𝗿𝘁𝗮𝗻𝘁: 𝗦𝗲𝗿𝘃𝗶𝗰𝗲 𝗨𝗽𝗱𝗮𝘁𝗲\n\nDue to high winds, all sailings on Friday 12th May are cancelled.\n\nUpdates to follow.\n\n---\n\nADDITION EXAMPLE:\n🟢 𝗘𝘅𝘁𝗿𝗮 𝗦𝗮𝗶𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘀 𝗔𝗱𝗱𝗲𝗱\n\nFor the May Day long weekend, extra crossings are added on Saturday 3rd & Sunday 4th May.\n\n👉 Book your seat: GozoHighspeed.com	2026-04-29 21:17:02.614417
3	2	Booking Reminder	Direct, useful, mildly urgent — but never pushy. Use real seat-availability cues only ('selling fast', 'last call', 'before it's too late'). No false drama.	Bold headline + 1-2 sentence body + CTA line. Three short blocks separated by blank lines.	Sans-Serif Bold headline naming the specific scarcity — a sailing time, a route, a date, or a peak window. Triggers: peak weekends, specific times of day filling up, event dates. No 🔴 emoji on booking reminders.	Own line at the end, prefixed with 👉. The verb can vary to fit the post: 'Book Now', 'Reserve your seat', 'Secure your spot', 'Save your seat' all work. Always ends with the domain in CamelCase: GozoHighspeed.com.	Exclamation marks, ALL CAPS, false drama, countdown emojis (⏰ ⏳), vague 'book now' without context, hashtags. NEVER frame seats as inventory/stock — banned phrasings: 'before it's gone', 'before it fills up', 'before it sells out', 'don't miss', 'limited time', 'hurry', 'do not miss out'. Time-based urgency about the journey itself IS allowed because it's true to the service: 'before it's too late', 'last call'. If the body already says 'selling fast', do NOT add a second urgency line — let the CTA do the rest.	𝗟𝗮𝘀𝘁 𝗖𝗮𝗹𝗹 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝟬𝟳:𝟰𝟱 𝘁𝗼 𝗩𝗮𝗹𝗹𝗲𝘁𝘁𝗮\n\nSeats for the 07:45 on Thursday 30th April are selling fast. Secure your place onboard before it's too late.\n\n👉 Book Now: GozoHighspeed.com	2026-04-29 21:11:36.5851
2	2	Fleet Highlight	Casual, observational, lightly playful. Sounds like an Instagram caption from a fan of the boats, not a marketing department. Atmospheric, sometimes personified ('she's already making waves'). The image leads — the caption is a one-line quip that frames the moment.	ONE short line. Sentence fragment is fine. Often trails off with '…' or '..' or ends with a single emoji like 🌊. NO bold headline, NO multi-block structure, NO blank lines. Two short lines max if absolutely needed.	Plain sentence case. NO Sans-Serif Bold formatting. NO flag emoji at the start. The line IS the post — there's no headline-then-body structure here.\n\nNOUN POLICY: NEVER call them 'boat' or 'ship'. Refer to the vessel as: a ferry, a vessel, the fleet, or 'she'/'her' (personified). NEVER invent or assume a vessel name. Only use a vessel name if the brief explicitly gives one — most posts don't name the vessel at all.\n\nCOHERENCE: The line must read as ONE complete thought, not two fragments stitched with 'and'. BAD: 'mid-channel, and she's already on her way back 🌊' — two half-ideas glued together; neither stands alone, the connection makes no logical sense. GOOD: 'Smooth sailing into the weekend like…' — one whole observation.\n\nOBSERVABILITY: Describe what the image shows, not what came before or after. AVOID temporal narrative the photo can't carry: 'already on her way back', 'returning from', 'after a long day', 'just dropped off'. Stick to what's visible: the place, the light, the moment.\n\nDON'T TEMPLATE THE ANCHORS: The construction 'and she's already X' worked once because of specific context (a new vessel + the natural metaphor 'making waves'). Do NOT reuse it as a formula. Vary the construction every time.\n\nSPECIFICITY: Anchor to a real GHS detail. Strongest anchors (in order of preference):\n1. LOCATION — Sliema, Bugibba, Mġarr, the Sliema waterfront, mid-channel.\n2. MOMENT — golden hour, the weekend, crossover, first light, last crossing of the day.\n3. PERSONIFICATION — used sparingly, with something genuinely observable (not narrative).\n4. VESSEL NAME — only if explicitly given in the brief.\n\nIt is often best to skip a vessel noun entirely. If the line could be slapped on any ferry photo anywhere in the world, it's too generic. Don't lead with a bare plural noun ('two ferries passing') unless paired with a specific moment or place.\n\nExamples of acceptable openings:\n- 'Smooth sailing into the weekend like…'\n- 'Sailing into style at the Port of Valletta'\n- 'The fastest fleet on the waters'\n- 'The Sliema waterfront just got a new regular .. and she's already making waves 🌊'	NONE. NEVER include 👉, NEVER include a 🌐 link line, NEVER write 'GozoHighspeed.com' anywhere in the post, NEVER use 'book', 'reserve', 'plan your', or any call to action. End on the line itself. This is not a sales post — it's a showcase. The image does the work.	Bold headlines (Sans-Serif Bold or otherwise). Multi-block structure with blank lines. Spec-sheet language ('350 seats', '35 knots', capacity numbers, deck counts). Boastful labels ('our pride', 'flagship', 'state-of-the-art'). Generic adjectives ('amazing', 'incredible', 'stunning'). CTAs, links, booking nudges, the brand domain. Don't over-explain — let the image carry it.\n\nBANNED NOUNS: 'boat', 'ship'. Use vessel, ferry, fleet, 'she', or named ONLY if the brief gives the name.\n\nINVENTED NAMES: NEVER invent or assume a vessel name. If the brief doesn't say which vessel, don't name one — describe the place, the moment, or use 'she'.\n\nINCOHERENT FRAGMENTS: never stitch two half-thoughts with 'and' just because each contains an approved element. Every line must read as ONE single coherent observation. If you wouldn't say it out loud as a normal sentence, rewrite it.\n\nNARRATIVE INFERENCE: never describe a state the image can't show. Banned: 'already on her way back', 'returning from', 'after a long day', 'just dropped off', 'about to depart' (unless the photo clearly shows de